fields.text:
GRAND RAPIDS -- The number of homes sold last month in the Grand Rapids area and the average price of
those sales is up from February and from a year ago.
More than 1,200 homes were sold in the Grand Rapids area last month, up 28 percent from a year ago, as
buyers take advantage of the federal tax credit and low interest rates.
The total, 1,244 homes, is higher than March totals going back to 2006 and is almost as high as 2005's 1,270.
Stephanie Dufford of Five Star Real Estate in Grandville said spring traditionally is busy.
"But it has been kind of lacking the last few years," she said. "We're all looking at each other saying, 'Oh my
gosh, we're having a spring market.'"
Real estate agents are enjoying the boost now, knowing when the federal home buyer tax credit expires April
30, sales could plummet again.
The sales boost marks 14 straight months of year-over-year increases, according to the Grand Rapids
Association of Realtors.
Sellers also can cheer: The average sale price of $113,883 is up 13 percent from March 2010 but still far below
the $153,579 of 2005. Year-to-date, the average sale price is $110,649, up 14 percent from this time last year.
The portion of those transactions that were short sales or foreclosures is down from the previous four months to
45 percent.
The sales boost helps put the inventory in a good range. At 8,252, there are between six and seven months of
listings on the market.
Julie Rietberg, chief executive of the association, said that is the "normal pre-recession range."
fields.headline: March home sales -- and prices-- see increases

fields.text:
GRAND RAPIDS -- Liz Keegan is resting a little easier.
The 33-year-old Eastown resident recently secured a signed purchase agreement to buy her first home, a brick
house on Diamond Avenue NE overlooking a cemetery.
And the agreement comes in plenty of time to qualify for the $8,000 first-time homebuyer federal tax credit,
which requires signed agreements by April 30. Deals must close by June 30.
Like many others trying to take advantage of the tax credit, Keegan's house hunting took on a bit of urgency. In
the week before she made the offer, she toured at least a dozen homes, feeling the deadline pressure.
"The tax credit really gave me the incentive," she said.
That is part of the reason Grand Rapids-area home sales last month soared to levels not seen since 2005. And
April is expected to be bustling, too.
Keegan's real estate agent, Doretha Ardoin of Midwest Properties, said she has five clients on a serious hunt,
hoping to snag the credit. And her listings are seeing more activity, too.
"Homes that never had a showing in two months now get a showing every other day," she said.
While it still is a buyer's market, the looming deadline is making things interesting.
Much of the inventory is bank-owned or subject to a short sale, complicating the transaction and often causing
delays, Ardoin said.
"The ones that are good houses, that are normal transactions, are getting picked off quickly with multiple offers,"
she said. "It's becoming quite competitive. It feels like old times."
Stephanie Dufford, an agent with Five Star Real Estate, said some of her clients are getting nervous and
considering "settling" for anything rather than missing the credit.
"In fact, I had a case of somebody not too long ago, they were almost ready to write an offer on two different
houses simultaneously," she said. "It's getting so competitive."
Dufford said the market is ripe for sellers as well as buyers, if they can afford to take the prices this market
yields. While last month's average sale price of $113,883 is 13 percent higher than a year ago, it still is down 26
percent from 2005.
"If a seller wants to really take advantage of this time, they've got a month," Dufford said. "If the price is right,
their house could very easily sell within a month.
"It's better, even if it's not in perfect shape, just to get it on the market."
Experts also warn that interest rates, now attractively low, have nowhere to go but up.
This week's average 30-year fixed rate of 5.23 percent already is 12 basis points higher than last week,
according to financial Web site Bankrate.com. And the Web site's weekly survey showed 69 percent of
respondents expect rates to go higher still.
"They probably will continue to rise through the summer and beyond," Bankrate Senior Editor Chris Kissell said.
"Most experts will tell you that rates are at historic lows right now, and we probably won't see these kind of
numbers again for a long time."
"You've got low rates, low prices and you've got a tax credit," Kissell continued. "It's like a hat trick there, and
that's going to end real soon."
Eric Hendrickson, senior vice president of mortgage lending at Fifth Third Bank, said they are "extremely busy"
with home buyer loans rather than refinancing requests.
"Last month, more than 60 percent of our applications were purchase applications. Usually it's the other way
around," he said. "Our operations group, right now they are working overtime to keep up with the demand."
And for those who secure that purchase agreement before the April 30 deadline, the two-month window until
June 30 should be plenty of time to close the deal, said Sarah Baar, an assistant vice president and mortgage
loan officer at Founders Bank & Trust.
A typical, conventional loan can close in about three weeks, she said, while government loans may take an
additional week.
"It's sort of nice that we've been given that two-month time frame as lenders," she said. "Some underwriting is
taking a little bit longer than it had in the past."
The real crunch may come for title companies at the end of June.
Steve Barnum, vice president of marketing and sales for Transnation Title Agency of Michigan, said they will be
ready for that final push.
"From what we're seeing, the closings have definitely been affected by the credit," he said. "There's been more
business as a result of that."
And what happens to the housing market when the credit expires?
Bryan Myrick, an agent with Coldwell Banker Woodland Schmidt in Holland, is hopeful the market will continue
to be strong.
"I'm concerned about it," he said. "But out of the six buyers I have that could pull the trigger anytime, only two
want to really do it before the deadline."
Ardoin said she tries to be optimistic.
"But I do believe there will be a trickle down."
fields.headline: Homebuyers are on the prowl - Low prices, federal tax credit deadline provide double incentive

fields.text: LOWELL -- A 71-year-old man who operated a day care with his wife at their Lowell home is accused of sexually assaulting a female relative in late February. Police say the girl is not a day care client. Wayne Chamberlain was arraigned in 63rd District Court on a charge of second-degree criminal sexual conduct. Police said the child was visiting the residence Feb. 26 when the assault occurred. The child was watching television with a blanket over her lap when Chamberlain allegedly touched her inappropriately. The day care was operating at the time, Kent County sheriff's deputies said. Deputies said the couple's state license for Carol's Day Care has been suspended. Chamberlain is free on $10,000 bond and is scheduled for a Wednesday preliminary exam before Judge Sara Smolenski. Police ask any clients of Carol's Day Care with concerns about the alleged incident to call the Kent County sheriff's investigative division at 336-5183.
fields.headline: Man charged in assault

fields.text:
MUSKEGON -- Dennis Porter never expected to get personal mail at his workplace. Still less did he expect what he got last week.
The retired Muskegon County sheriff's deputy works part time at the metal-detection line in the Michael E. Kobza Hall of Justice. About 10 days ago, in the middle of his afternoon shift, a county staffer handed him a sealed envelope addressed to Porter and marked "personal."
The deputy's surprise heightened to astonishment when he opened the envelope. Inside were two folded sheets of paper.
One was blank and held a $100 bill.
The other was an unsigned note expressing contrition for a theft of cigarettes from Porter's grandmother's store -- more than 40 years ago.
"I should have made this right a long time ago, but years go (by) and you say I'll do it later," the note read.
"A few weeks ago I was told that I have cancer," the note continued. "When you get this kind of news, you think about things you should have done a long time ago. Please forgive me. I would think that your grandmother is passed on so I'm sending you the money with interest."
For more than a quarter century Henrietta Porter ran a neighborhood grocery store she inherited from her parents, the Sidney Temple Grocery. In 1969, she sold it and retired. The store -- even the address, 837 E. Forest -- no longer exists.
Henrietta Porter lived many more years, but the anonymous letter-writer was right: She died in December 2005 at the age of 95.
"I read it, and it just dumbstruck me," Dennis Porter said of the letter. "If that person had stolen those cigarettes on the very last day she was open for business, it's been haunting that person for 41 years.
"My grandmother was a very devout Christian," he said. "She'd have scolded them strongly. Their ears would probably still be ringing.
"But she would have forgiven them. I want them to know that: They are forgiven."
Within a couple of days, Porter put the money to good use. He bought a cell phone with minutes for his 82-year-old mother, Henrietta's daughter Marilyn Porter of Traverse City, to wear around her neck in case of emergency.
Dennis Porter said his grandmother lived in an apartment behind the store. "I spent an enormous amount of my
childhood there," he said. "We knew all the neighbor kids. We played. You were outdoors all the time. "I grew up and went into the service, and while I was gone, she closed that store."
Porter served in the Marine Corps in 1967-69, stationed in California. He was 19 when the family store was sold.
He has no idea who sent him the note and the money and doesn't really want to find out.
He can only speculate: "I'm sure it's somebody I know. I almost feel it's somebody I grew up with over there. They probably came through the (county) building recently and saw me, though I don't remember anyone coming up and saying 'Hey, Den.'"
Porter has one wish for the long-ago thief who made the anonymous atonement.
"I want to make sure this person finds peace over something that simple," he said. "I think a pack of cigarettes in 1969 was 39 cents or less. I just want them to know, by this article, that she would forgive them."

fields.headline: 40 years later, dying thief pays for stolen cigarettes - $100 sent anonymously to store owner's grandson as way of atonement

fields.text:
GRAND RAPIDS -- The Bible might be the best book -- or cake -- Justin Lawrence ever tasted.
Calvin College celebrated its first book-eating contest Thursday with baked stories about Peter Rabbit, Winnie
the Pooh, The Very Hungry Caterpillar and The Scarlet Letter.
The cakes, cookies, cupcakes and pies that resembled or were inspired by famous books were so delicious that
Lawrence, who works at the campus store, suggested, "If people need more food, maybe we should cut up the
Bible."
"It's a very Eastery cake," Lawrence said, pointing to a Scripture verse on the cake that talked about Good
Friday -- which is today -- preceding Easter by two days.
Calvin librarian Lois Dye, a self-proclaimed "foodie," founded Books in the Baking this year after learning about
the International Edible Book Festival, a similar contest that has been celebrated worldwide on April Fool's Day
-- or as they like to call it, Edible Book Day -- since 2000.
"I hope it sheds a different light that libraries can be fun, and not just rigid," she said. "Anytime I can combine my
love of books and baking, I look for an event."
On Wednesday night, Calvin juniors Rose Bosscher and Jen Erickson scrambled to finish baking their book.
Along with several friends, they made three Meijer grocery store runs to pick up Fruit Roll-ups, Twizzlers, and
frosting for their bright green cookie sheet about the story "If You Give a Mouse a Cookie."
Afterward, it wasn't easy for them to let go of their artwork as they watched students chow down.
"If people want to take pictures, we want them to take pictures," Bosscher said. "We don't want to ruin it."
Freshman Paula Manni won the People's Choice award with her depiction of "The Tale of Peter Rabbit."
Libraries around the world hold book-eating contests in April. The idea has spread to nearly 20 countries,
including England, Italy and Japan.
fields.headline: Book lovers eat their words - Food contest won't settle for half-baked story ideas

fields.text:
PLAINFIELD TOWNSHIP -- An 82-year-old woman's car went through the front window of a hair salon
Thursday, leaving two people with minor injuries. The woman said her foot slipped off the brake as she was
pulling into a parking space outside Classic Hair Design, 3910 Plainfield Ave. NE, about 11:30 a.m. The car
went through the floor-to-ceiling window. Kent County sheriff's Lt. Kevin Kelley said police expected to issue the
woman a ticket.
fields.headline: Car hits salon window

fields.text:
WYOMING -- An administrative aide who was appointed interim director of the Housing Commission last month
now has been hired for the job. Rebeca Geerling replaces the retired Helen Haight as chief of the city agency
that manages 195 subsidized public housing units in Wyoming and administers federally funded rent vouchers
for 1,122 private units in Kent and Ottawa counties. A five-member board oversees operations of the
commission, which has 12 full-time staff with an office at Westwood Apartments.
fields.headline: Interim director gets housing job

fields.text:
GRAND RAPIDS -- A former vice president of First Bank of West Michigan pleaded guilty Thursday to allegations he used others' personal information to obtain loans -- and then took out additional loans to pay the money back.
Michael Willett, 40, pleaded guilty to theft of bank funds, which carries a maximum penalty of 30 years in prison, and aggravated identity theft, a two-year felony to be served consecutively.
Fourteen other charges will be dismissed as part of a plea agreement.
The guilty pleas revolved around loans that Willett took out in his uncle's name. He used his uncle's tax return and driver's license to obtain personal information.
The uncle, who was reimbursed by Willett's father, was unaware he had been victimized, Willett said. "I did use the funds for my personal use," he told U.S. Magistrate Judge Ellen Carmody.
Assistant U.S. Attorney Matthew Borgula said Willett took $336,000 in fraudulent loans, but much of the money was used to repay earlier loans.
Restitution at this point is $67,293.
Court records show Willett, who also said manager of the Lowell branch, used customers' personal identification to obtain loans between 2005 and 2007.
Willett, in court with attorney David Kaczor, will be sentenced later. He is free on bond.
In February, another First Bank officer, former Belding Mayor Shane Husted, was sentenced to 18 months in prison for stealing $70,000 from the bank. Husted worked as a security officer who would investigate thefts of bank funds.

fields.text: HUDSONVILLE -- Sunrise Park again will be the home of Freedom Christian's middle school baseball team, pending formal approval this month by Hudsonville officials. The private school will get free use of the field in the city park at the end of Springdale Street, east of Balsam Drive, through May 20. Practices are planned 3-4:30 p.m. two to three days per week, with 4 p.m. games scheduled April 19, 20, 27 and 29 and May 6, 11, 18 and 20.
